msContents.summary: This is a fifteenth-century manuscript from Northern Italy, possibly Verona, which contains Sulpicius Severus' Life of Saint Martin and his Dialogues; Gregory of Tours' Life of Saint Martin of Tours; Tituli Metrici de Sancto Martino; and the Life of Saint Zeno.

msItem.title: Sulpicius Severus, Life of Saint Martin, Prologue, Table of Contents
msItem.incipit: [S]EVERVS Desiderio fratri karissimo salutem. Ego quidem frater unanimis libellum quem de uita Sancti Martini scripseram seda sua comprimere et intra domesticos parietes cohibere decreueram
msItem.explicit: Subueniat lapsis memor ipse sue pietatis.

msItem.title: Sulpicius Severus, Life of Saint Martin
msItem.incipit: Plerique mortalium studio et glorie seculari innaniter dediti exinde perhennem ut putabant memoriam nominis sui quesierunt.
msItem.explicit: Martinus habrahe sinu letus excipitur. Martinus hic pauper et modicus celum diues ingreditur.

msItem.title: Sulpicius Severus, Dialogue I
msItem.incipit: [C]um in unum locum ego et Gallus noster conuenissemus uir mihi et propter Martini memoriam ex illius enim discipulis erat et propter sua merita carissimus
msItem.explicit: Unde prima illius interim mutilando gesta pretereo neque ea attingam que laycus egit ac Monachus nec vero audita ab aliis potius quamque uidi ipse dicturus sum.

msItem.title: Sulpicius Severus, Dialogue II
msItem.incipit: [Q]uo primo igitur tempore relictis scolis beato me uiro iunxi paucos post dies euntem ad ecclesiam sequebamur.
msItem.explicit: Uerum quia de Martini uirtutibus nequaquam explicari uniuersa potuerunt, hec nobis hodie audisse sufficiat, cras reliqua dicemus. Ita pariter accepta sponsione surreximus.

msItem.title: Sulpicius Severus, Dialogue III
msItem.incipit: [L]ucessit o Galle surgendum est. Nam ut uides et Postumianus instat. Et hic presbiter qui hesterno auditorium amisit.
msItem.explicit: Nec cum maxime flebili uoce gemeremus omnium lacrimis per nostra lamenta commotis, cum magna quidem Martini admiratione sed non minore ex nostris flectibus [sic] dolore discessum est.

msItem.title: Gregory of Tours, Life of Saint Martin of Tours
msItem.incipit: [C]lemens trinitas et una diuinitas ut autem per sacramentum cognoscatur. Unitas est ab eo et qui est spiritus sanctus
msItem.explicit: Nos uero de quanto nostro tempore aut fieri uidimus aut factum certe cognouimus silere nequiuimus.

msItem.title: Tituli Metrici de Sancto Martino
msItem.incipit: Uenimus en istuc hic nemo personat heu
msItem.explicit: Quarta die ipsius mensis missam deuotissime celebrabis. hoc si feceris et in presenti seculo et in futuro patrocinia illius promerebis. Lege ut credas, crede ut uiuas in eternum. DEO GRATIAS.

msItem.title: Life of Saint Zeno
msItem.incipit: Eo tempore quo Ualerianus cum filio Galieno fasces Romani Imperii suscepit
msItem.explicit: quam palam artifex durus nocuit qui magis dolis et regnis quam uiribis confidit protinus sacerdotes apertis inditiis Satam inter filios dei uenisse cognouerunt.

supportDesc.extent: i+90+i; 201 x 140 mm bound to 214 x 150 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Foliation in ink, upper right recto; some refoliation in pencil, upper right recto

p.catchwords: Horizontal catchwords centered in lower margin, verso, accompanied by four similar flourishes above, below, and on both sides

layoutDesc.layout: Single column, twenty-eight to twenty-nine lines, ruled with single vertical bounding lines, full length, occasionally with single horizontal bounding lines above the ruled lines; prickings in upper and lower margins

decoDesc.decoNote: Four two-line red initials; spaces for all other initials left unfilled with guide letters for decorator visible; headings and tables of contents in red, almost totally faded

binding.p: Original wooden boards with eighteenth-century blind-tooled leather backing, leather and metal clasp; on spine, gold-tooled: SEU. SVLPITII/ VITA S. MARTINI MSS; On back cover in ink: "Vita B. Martini"

history.provenance: Written in the fifteenth century; the inclusion of the Life of Zeno suggests that it may have been written in Verona, that saint's diocese; early provenance unknown; library shelf mark: "533" in ink and on a paper label on inside front cover; on verso of folio i: "MS 32"; two unidentified catalogue entries glued to inside cover, # 5335 and #139; in lead on inside back cover: "#12884"; in the collection of Sir John Hadden Hindley (1765-1827; bookplate); Sir Thomas Phillipps (MS 6732 on fol. 1r, listed in the Catalogus librorum manuscriptorum) acquired it in 1834 from Howell and Steward; in the collection of Howard L. Goodhart (bookplate), and presented by him to Bryn Mawr College (bookplate) in 1943
